article.headline: Air Force 51, New Mexico 46
article.story: AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- Air Force would much rather win games with its defense. They did just that Wednesday night, holding New Mexico to its lowest total of the season in the Falcons' 51-46 win over the Lobos -- their fourth straight. "Our defense is the staple of our program," said Antoine Hood, who led the Falcons with 16 points. "Offense is a variable, but defense is where you can pick it up. Tonight, you've just got to put (the win) on our defense." Dan Nwaelele and Matt McCraw each added 10 points -- both making three 3-pointers -- for the Falcons, who extended their home winning streak to 14 games this season and 16 overall and tied a school record with 22 wins in one season. The Falcons finished 22-7 during the 2003-04 season. Mark Walters led the Lobos with 17 points, while David Chiotti scored 12 points and grabbed 11 rebounds for New Mexico (16-10, 7-6). The Lobos had scored 47 points in their win last Wednesday over Wyoming, but could not pull out another low-scoring victory. The Falcons (22-5, 10-4) lead the nation in scoring defense, allowing 53.8 points a game coming into Wednesday, and they confounded the Lobos the entire game. New Mexico shot 37.3 percent from the field (19-of-51) and scored just 18 points before halftime -- also its lowest first-half total of the season. "A six-point lead for Air Force is like a 12-point lead for somebody else, because of their defense," Chiotti said. Air Force also controlled the tempo, forcing the Lobos to play a slow, deliberate half-court game. Neither team scored any fast-break points. But even when they got good looks, the Lobos couldn't knock down their shots, instead watching the ball rim out or circle the hoop before falling outside the basket. "Our defense is controlling the game, but we've got to knock down some shots behind it," New Mexico coach Ritchie McKay said. McCraw's 3-pointer gave the Falcons a 35-28 lead with 7:48 remaining, but the Lobos climbed back, helped by Air Force's poor free-throw shooting down the stretch. The Falcons missed five throws in the game's final 4:29. Walters and Kellen Walter each hit 3-pointers late in the game to pull New Mexico within two points with a minute remaining. Both teams made five 3-pointers in the second half. McCraw made one free throw, then missed his second with 33 seconds remaining to make it 47-44. But Chiotti lost the ball out-of-bounds in front of the Air Force bench after McCraw's miss, giving the Falcons the ball back. Hood couldn't seal the win with 22.9 seconds left, making just one free throw. Chad Toppert then hit a shot under the basket to make it 48-46 with 16.6 remaining. Jacob Burtschi then made two free throws and Hood added another for the final margin. The win coupled with San Diego State's 100-90 loss Wednesday to BYU puts the Falcons just one game behind the Aztecs for the conference lead. Air Force has a good chance of winning out the rest of its regular season. The Falcons play UNLV Saturday at home, then face the struggling CSU Rams in their final game. They've beaten both teams once already. "Right now, we have our swagger back," McCraw said.
